TASK_TITLE=Mouse UX: text selection, copy, and standard terminal mouse behavior in doey tmux
TASK_STATUS=done
TASK_TYPE=feature
TASK_CREATED_BY=boss
TASK_TEAM=0
TASK_DESCRIPTION=User wants standard terminal mouse behaviors in doey tmux sessions: select text with mouse, copy with Ctrl+C, scroll with mousewheel, etc. Currently tmux mouse mode likely captures events for pane operations, breaking text selection.

What needs to work:
1. Click and drag to select text in any pane
2. Ctrl+C (or Cmd+C on macOS terminal) to copy selected text to system clipboard
3. Mousewheel scroll through pane history/scrollback
4. Right-click paste (if terminal supports it)
5. Double-click to select word, triple-click to select line
6. All of this without breaking: pane switching, pane resizing, tmux status bar clicks

RESEARCH:
- What is doey's current tmux mouse config? Check shell/doey.sh and shell/tmux-statusbar.sh for 'set -g mouse' or 'set-option' mouse settings
- What tmux version is on this box? (tmux -V)
- What terminal emulator does the user connect with? (SSH client + terminal app)
- tmux mouse mode trade-offs: 'set -g mouse on' enables pane click/resize/scroll but captures mouse from terminal, breaking text selection. Fix options:
  a) Hold Shift while selecting (tmux passes Shift+click through to terminal) — works but user must know the trick
  b) tmux copy-mode: mouse drag enters copy mode, selection copies to tmux buffer, then pipe to system clipboard via 'tmux save-buffer - | xclip' or similar
  c) tmux 3.1+ has 'copy-pipe-and-cancel' for mouse drag -> system clipboard
  d) set-option -g mouse off in doey config (gives terminal back full mouse, but loses pane click/resize)
  e) Hybrid: mouse on, but configure copy-mode-vi or copy-mode-emacs with mouse drag -> clipboard bindings
  f) Conditional: hold a modifier key to toggle behavior

RECOMMENDED APPROACH: tmux copy-mode with clipboard integration. When user drags mouse:
  1. tmux enters copy-mode
  2. Selection highlights text
  3. On mouse release: copy selection to system clipboard (via OSC 52 escape sequence for SSH, or xclip/pbcopy for local)
  4. Exit copy-mode automatically
  This gives the user mouse select + copy without losing pane click/resize.

OSC 52 is KEY for remote/SSH usage — it tells the terminal to set clipboard directly, bypassing the need for xclip on the server. Most modern terminals support it (iTerm2, kitty, alacritty, WezTerm, Windows Terminal, ghostty).

IMPLEMENTATION: Add tmux config to doey session initialization (shell/doey.sh or wherever tmux options are set for the session). Something like:
  set -g mouse on
  set -g set-clipboard on
  bind-key -T copy-mode MouseDragEnd1Pane send-keys -X copy-pipe-and-cancel
  bind-key -T copy-mode-vi MouseDragEnd1Pane send-keys -X copy-pipe-and-cancel
  (Exact bindings depend on tmux version — 3.1+ vs 2.x have different syntax)

Also configure Ctrl+C in copy-mode to cancel selection (not kill process).

ACCEPTANCE:
1. In a doey session, mouse-drag to select text in a pane — text highlights
2. Release mouse — selection copies to clipboard (verify with paste in another app)
3. Mousewheel scrolls pane history
4. Clicking a different pane still switches to it
5. Pane border drag still resizes
6. Ctrl+C on running process still sends SIGINT (not captured by copy mode)
7. Works over SSH from user's laptop terminal
8. Fresh-install: config applied by doey session startup, not user-local tmux.conf
